const summary="'`Dataset ds001_prostate contained ${n} patients and an overall objective_response rate of ${pct(ybar)}. I treated objective_response as a binary outcome and used response-risk differences as the natural-scale effect estimate. Tests were two-proportion z tests for simple subgroups, delta-method risk-difference contrasts for interactions, and HC1 robust linear-probability models for adjusted analyses.

The strongest main-effect findings were binary. feature_005=1 was associated with much higher response (${pct(R.f005.p1)} vs ${pct(R.f005.p0)}, ${pp(R.f005.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.f005.p)}). In contrast, feature_034=1 was associated with lower response (${pct(R.f034.p1)} vs ${pct(R.f034.p0)}, ${pp(R.f034.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.f034.p)}). feature_009=1 and feature_065=1 each had about a ${pp(-0.1005)} adverse difference, and the rarer feature_055=1 had a ${pp(R.f055.effect)} difference. feature_067 and feature_025 were weak/null comparators and did not meet p<0.05.

Continuous and ordinal features added additional structure. Upper-quartile feature_003 (>=${t003hi}) was strongly adverse (${pp(R.f003high.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.f003high.p)}), while lower-quartile feature_003 (<=${t003lo}) was favorable (${pp(R.f003low.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.f003low.p)}). Upper-quartile feature_063 and feature_054 were also adverse, and higher feature_027 was modestly favorable. feature_023 showed a clear level gradient: level 2 had lower response than level 0 (${pct(R.f023_2v0.p1)} vs ${pct(R.f023_2v0.p0)}, ${pp(R.f023_2v0.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.f023_2v0.p)}). In contrast, upper-quartile feature_039 and feature_040 level 10 versus 6 were not meaningfully associated with response.

The dominant interaction was feature_005 by feature_034. The feature_005 response advantage was ${pp(R.f005_f034.cells['"'10'].p-R.f005_f034.cells['00'].p)} when feature_034=0 but only "'${pp(R.f005_f034.cells['"'11'].p-R.f005_f034.cells['01'].p)} when feature_034=1; the interaction contrast was "'${pp(R.f005_f034.effect)} (p=${ptxt(R.f005_f034.p)}). This made feature_005=1 and feature_034=0 a high-response subgroup (${pct(R.fav.p1)} vs ${pct(R.fav.p0)} for all others, ${pp(R.fav.effect)}).

Other binary features modified the favorable feature_005 pattern. The feature_005 association was smaller in feature_009=1 patients (interaction ${pp(R.f005_f009.effect)}), feature_065=1 patients (${pp(R.f005_f065.effect)}), and feature_055=1 patients (${pp(R.f005_f055.effect)}), all significant. The adverse effects of feature_009 and feature_065 were much smaller inside the feature_034=1 subgroup, suggesting overlapping low-response strata rather than simple additive penalties. The feature_065 by feature_009 interaction was positive (${pp(R.f065_f009.effect)}), also consistent with nonadditive overlap.

feature_003 was the continuous feature most tied to heterogeneity. Upper-quartile feature_003 reduced response only modestly when feature_005=0 but sharply when feature_005=1; the interaction contrast was ${pp(R.f003high_f005.effect)} (p=${ptxt(R.f003high_f005.p)}). By contrast, the upper-quartile feature_003 by feature_034 interaction and the upper-quartile feature_063 by feature_005 interaction were not significant.

Composite strata sharpened the pattern. Any of feature_009, feature_065, or feature_055 identified a low-response group (${pp(R.adverseAny.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.adverseAny.p)}). Both feature_003>=${t003hi} and feature_063>=${t063hi} identified a very low-response group (${pct(R.bioHighBoth.p1)}, ${pp(R.bioHighBoth.effect)}), while feature_003<=${t003lo} with feature_063=0 identified a favorable group (${pct(R.bioLowFavorable.p1)}, ${pp(R.bioLowFavorable.effect)}). The highest-response subgroup found was feature_005=1, feature_034=0, and no feature_009/feature_065/feature_055 flags: ${pct(R.favNoAdverse.p1)} response versus ${pct(R.favNoAdverse.p0)} in all others (${pp(R.favNoAdverse.effect)}, p=${ptxt(R.favNoAdverse.p)}).

Adjusted models supported the same conclusions. In a main-effects linear-probability model, feature_005 remained positive (${pp(O.main.feature_005.beta)}), feature_034 remained negative (${pp(O.main.feature_034.beta)}), feature_009, feature_065, and feature_055 remained negative, feature_003/feature_063/feature_054 remained adverse, and feature_027 remained favorable. feature_039 stayed null after adjustment. In the interaction model, feature_005:feature_034 (${pp(O.interaction['"'feature_005:feature_034'].beta)}) and feature_005:feature_009 ("'${pp(O.interaction['"'feature_005:feature_009'].beta)}) remained strongly negative, while standardized feature_003 remained independently adverse ("'${pp(O.interaction.feature_003_z.beta)} per SD).

Overall, the cohort appears dominated by a favorable feature_005 signal that is highly conditional on feature_034 and further weakened by feature_009, feature_065, feature_055, and high feature_003. Because all features are de-identified and this is observational EHR-derived data, these are association patterns rather than causal treatment effects.`;
